        "suggested_read": "['PMBOK® Guide - 7th Edition: 3.3.1.2 Leadership', 'Situational Leadership® Model by Hersey and Blanchard']",
        "concepts_to_understand": "The Situational Leadership® model emphasizes adapting leadership to the maturity of the follower. A mature team, defined by both high competence and high commitment, requires minimal oversight. The Delegating (S4) style is the most hands-off approach, empowering the team to take full ownership, which is the hallmark of a high-performing project team.",
        "additional_notes": "This question focuses on the 'delegating' stage of the Situational Leadership® model, which is the ultimate goal for many project managers—to have a self-managing team. The scenario provides all the keywords: 'highly productive,' 'high technical expertise,' 'strong cohesion,' and 'independently solving problems.' These descriptors clearly point to a team that is both competent and committed (R4). Therefore, the project manager's role shifts from a leader to a facilitator, providing resources and removing impediments rather than providing direction or support. The incorrect options represent leadership styles for less mature teams, making them easily distinguishable from the correct answer.",
        "difficulty_level": "easy"
