        "tool": "ADKAR® (Change Model)",
        "suggested_read": "['PMBOK® Guide - 7th Edition: 3.3.1.2 Leadership', 'Prosci® ADKAR® Model']",
        "concepts_to_understand": "The ADKAR® model is a goal-oriented change management model. ADKAR is an acronym for Awareness, Desire, Knowledge, Ability, and Reinforcement. It provides a structured approach to ensure individuals successfully adopt change. 'Desire' is the critical step of personal motivation and willingness to participate. Without 'Desire,' change adoption will likely fail, even if Awareness, Knowledge, and Ability are in place.",
        "additional_notes": "This is a straightforward question that tests the core components of the ADKAR® model. The keywords 'resisting' and 'reluctant' directly point to a lack of 'Desire.' The scenario explicitly states that technical training and documentation are available, which rules out Knowledge, Awareness, and Ability as the primary issue. The challenge is in correctly identifying which of the five steps is the root cause of the resistance. The core of the ADKAR® model is that each step must be achieved in sequence; if one is missing, the change will not succeed. In this case, the missing step is 'Desire.'",
